x4freetext: The experiments at  50-71 MeV
In NSD experiment stacks of three self-supporting
~600 mug/cm2 rhodium metal foils  interspersed  with
2-mg/cm2-thick Al foils were used.
In TRM targets of metallic rhodium of thickness
around 100 mu-gm/cm2 with 100 mu-gm/cm2 Al backing
were used. The catchers used were evaporated aluminum
foils, typically 100 mugm/cm2 thick.
precalibrated 60cc HPGe detector coupled
to a 4 K MCA.
12-C beam.
An irradiation time of about 1-2 hours was
selected according to the half lives of the
radioisotopes produced. The total charge collected for
each irradiation was about 400-600 microCoulombs.
Data were received from authors.
PACE2 code.
The errors on the cross section arises mostly
from:
Uncertainty in counting statistics (1-4%)
Uncertainty in target thickness (5 - 8%),
Uncertainty in detection efficiency (4%),
Uncertainty in beam fluence (<5%),
Uncertainty in gamma-ray intensity
values (5-10%).

x4freetext: -By authors.  The cross sections of the products 111-In
and 110-In agree with the theoretical predictions while
those of 109-In show an enhancement.  It can be
inferred that the products 110,111-In are formed from
the Complete Fusion  process while 109-In have
contributions from the Incomplete Fusion involving the
breakup of 12-C into alpha+8Be and the subsequent
fusion of 8Be with target forming 111In*.  This
incompletely fused composite nucleus emits further
neutrons forming 109-In.
